37. The prosody of Plautus is in some particulars differ- ent from the prosody which the student learns from Vergil and Horace, and the first impression received from his versification is of carelessness and license. This impres- sion, however, is incorrect; the departures from recognized usage are few, but the usageS, the ruleS, of versification in the time of Plautus were not so artificial as those of the Augustan age. There are two reasons for this. F irst‚ the meters of Plautus were imitated from the Greek meters of the New Comedy‚ which were less strict than the earlier dramatic meters or the lyric meters which were the models of Horace. Second, the prosody of a word is a part of its pronunciation; and the pronunciation os Latin changed greatly in the century and a half after the death of PlautuS, and at all periods the pronunciation of the literary Latin varied considerably from the unregulated utterance of con- versation. The peculiarities of prosody in Plautus are therefore not “poetic licenseS,” but are either survivals of early pronunciation or colloquialismS.
